Cars4U- Used Car Price Prediction¶

Objective¶

To explore and visualize the dataset, build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars, and generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Key Requirement¶

come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing

Data Dictionary¶

The data contains the different attributes of used cars sold in different locations. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  1. S.No.: Serial number
  2. Name: Name of the car which includes brand name and model name
  3. Location: Location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (cities)
  4. Year: Manufacturing year of the car
  5. Kilometers_driven: The total kilometers (a unit used to measure length or distance) driven in the car by the previous owner(s)
  6. Fuel_Type: The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  7. Transmission: The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic/Manual)
  8. Owner: Type of ownership
  9. Mileage: The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
  10. Engine: The displacement volume of the engine in CC
  11. Power: The maximum power of the engine in bhp
  12. Seats: The number of seats in the car
  13. New_Price: The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh INR = 100,000 INR)
  14. Price: The price of the used car in INR Lakhs

Data Exploration : High Level Summary¶

  1. Columns Mileage , Engine , Power , Seats and Price have some missing data .Rest of the columns do not have any missing data .
  2. Mileage , Engine ,Power should be numeric columns but they are appearing as object so we will have to analyze if it contains any string /nan and based on that need to remove those strings .
  3. There are no duplicate rows in this data set
  4. Price column which is going to be our indepedant variable has some missing data. Hence we have dropped those rows which had missing data.
  5. Fuel_Type , Transmission ,Location ,owner_type are categorical data and hence need to set it's data type as categorical.
  6. Column Name comprises of car maaking Comany name and Car Model some details about model so we will have name and get these columns separated to see how they are appearing in dataset.
  7. Sr. No column is just a counter so we have dropped it

 ## Function covertToNumeric will spllit data in incomming DF based on  separator  " " 
 ## and it  will  return 0th position as this contains actual number  and index 1 , 2 and further contains other strings.
In [ ]:
def covertToNumeric(colname):
  if isinstance(colname, str):
   return float((colname.split(' ')[0]))
  else:
    return np.nan
In [ ]:
position_cols=['Mileage','Power','Engine']
In [ ]:
# For all three three columns lets call covertToNumeric Function which will remove all strings from it and then return it as Float
# string likes  lkm/kg', 'kmpl'  can be seen in  columns Mileage , Engine and Power . Fucntion will remove theese string and and convert first part  to Float.
for colname in position_cols :
  carsData[colname]=carsData[colname].apply(covertToNumeric)

Treatment for Car Name Column¶

  1. We have analyzed Car Name as single string and also by separing it between Company name and Model .
  2. When we analyzed Name as single field there are 1876 unique combinations
  3. Hence For this analysis we will first add Company Name and Model as new columns in carsData data Frame .
  4. Then we checked counts for Company Name and Model ,they are also high so we will have take some cut off and based on that we will term all company Name and Model below that cut off as some random name say "Other"
  5. Based on values in Company Name counts and ModelCounts we can take cut of Company Name and Model .
  6. To code items as "Other " first For both Company Name and Model we will have to create Lookup list one for Company Name and one for Model .
  7. Next we will write Function which will check if Company Name/Model contains item from Lookup table if yes then keep value as is else replace with "Other"
In [ ]:
# Adding Company Name and Model to carsData 
carsData['CompanyName']=CarCompanyNameModel['CompanyName']
carsData['Model']=CarCompanyNameModel['Model']
In [ ]:
## Lookup  Master for Company Name  and Model which will be top 50 and 50 values Company Names and Model Name respectively 
Lookup_Master_companyName = CompanyNameCounts[CompanyNameCounts.values >= 50].index.tolist()
Lookup_Master_companyModel = ModelCounts[ModelCounts.values >= 50].index.tolist()
In [ ]:
def LookUpBasedConverition(inputDF,lookup,CName):
  car_temp=[]
 
  for i in range(inputDF.shape[0]): 
    check = 0  # to see of variable in data frame is matching with Lookup field
    for item in lookup:  
        if item in inputDF[CName].values[i] and check == 0: 
            car_temp.append(item)
            check = 1
    if check == 0:  
        car_temp.append("Others")
  inputDF[CName +"_revised"] = [item for item in car_temp]
  del car_temp

Lets plot box plot and histplot for all numerical variables using user defined function checkDistribution.

User defined function ,"checkDistribution" will plot Histplot and Box Plot for all numerical columns.In Boxplot we will add showmeans =true to show Mean value , which will help us in comparing mean and median values.

In [ ]:
# This Function will  use to  Plot Histplot and Box Plot for all numberical columns  . We will add Lines to show mean and Median 
# so we can check skewness of data . 
# we will pass data Frame and column name as variables 
def checkDistribution(dataframe,columnName):
     plt.figure(figsize=(20,8));
     plt.subplot(1,2,1)
     plt.title("Distribution for Variable "+ columnName, fontsize=15)
     sns.histplot(data=dataframe,x=columnName,kde=True ,bins=15)
     plt.axvline(np.mean(dataframe[columnName]), color='green', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
     plt.text(np.mean(dataframe[columnName])+0.15,30,'Mean = '+str(round(np.mean(dataframe[columnName]),1)),rotation=90, fontsize=12)
     plt.axvline(np.median(dataframe[columnName]), color='red', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram
     plt.text(np.median(dataframe[columnName])+0.15,30,'Median = '+str(round(np.median(dataframe[columnName]),1)),rotation=90, fontsize=12)
     # To plot Bolxplot and showing Mean value
     plt.subplot(1,2,2)
     plt.title("Boxplot for "+ columnName, fontsize=12)
     sns.boxplot(data=dataframe,x=columnName ,showmeans=True )

Observations :¶

  1. We could see that Training Model which had 4213 observations have R2 values as 0.76 which means 76 % times model is able to explainin variations in Used Cars Train Data .
  2. We could see that for Testing data ( out sample) 1806 observations have Root mean sque value( R2) as 0.814 which means 81 % times model is able to explain variation in Test Data for used cars.
  3. we tried removing Company Name and CarModelName from Train data and checked performance and then checked model performace including these two variables on model and we could see increase in score .
  4. We tried different cut off( only values above this number are considered and values below are termed as "others") value for Company Name and CarModelName and final Value taken are 50 .
  5. We could see that R2 value for Test data is in line with Training data which means Model is not Over fitting .

Conclusion¶

  1. We could see that we could predict selling Price of used cars with R2 rate 0.81 .
  2. During this process we observeed that Engine ,Power and price of new car have high co-relation with Price of old cars
  3. We added Transformations for Location ,trnasmission ,KM, Fuel type as they also have substancial influce on predicting sell value .
  4. We have done this analysis with limited data with additional data we can improve this model performance better .
